<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-017-122 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 510 472</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Nov 4 1991 v37 n1885 p4(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Conferees OK $291B DOD bill, bar new B-2 buy. ($291 billion Fiscal1992 Defense Authorization bill blocks B-2 bomber procurement, butauthorizes $3.4 billion in funding to continue research anddevelopment)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Barrett, Joyce.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Senate and House conferees blocked procurement of Northrop B-2Stealth bombers under the $291 billion Fiscal 1992 DefenseAuthorization bill, but authorized $3.4 billion in funding tocontinue research and development.andP;  The 15 aircraft currentlyunder construction will be completed.andP;  The immediate impact of thebill could benefit the aerospace industry for several years.andP;  Aloophole provides for the addition of one more B-2 bomber if theplane overcomes deficiencies.andP;  Northrop hopes to fill the B-2 voidby joining with McDonnell Douglas to produce the Navy's AX attackplane.andP;  The company maintains a 40 percent role in the productionof the Navy's F-18 fighter.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Northrop Corp. (Products).andO;Ticker:    NOC.andO;Topic:     AircraftAerospace engineeringAerospace industryUnited States. CongressDefense ContractsResearch and Development.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>